{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f70cc016-a8ff-4c26-bc3b-0214a7ecc5da","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n### 1. Get a shell into the container\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace` inside the container\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### 3. Find your process ID\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect the trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n### 5. Copy the `.nettrace` file out\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-file>.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### 6. Analyze\nOpen the `.nettrace` file in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert it:\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format speedscope\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If the .NET SDK isn't in the container image, use `dotnet-monitor` as a sidecar instead — it exposes a REST API for on-demand trace collection without modifying the app container.\n- For **event-based** profiling (GC, exceptions, contention), swap the profile: `--profile gc-verbose` or `--providers Microsoft-DotNETCore-SampleProfiler`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"227e5940-07bb-4e31-9c35-eec896be6a2a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code change task. I should provide concise, actionable guidance.\n\nLet me provide a practical answer based on my knowledge of .NET diagnostics in containerized environments.","outputTokens":437,"requestId":"401C:39A45D:62AD25F:6BB2EE4:69F15DA2"},"id":"8e910358-4e04-4fbb-997e-2495364c4ca6","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:23:56.349Z","parentId":"0f05ecf3-87f3-4a1f-8bfd-9b1b0b5a5eb8"}
